Class NaryTree

java.lang.Object
  dataStructures.NaryTree
All Implemented Interfaces:
Collection, TraversableCollection, Tree
public class NaryTree
extends java.lang.Object
implements Tree

NaryTree class A NaryTree is an implementation of a rooted, unordered tree in which each node of the tree can have an indeterminate number of child nodes. This tree is irregular in the sense that different nodes may have differing max numbers of child nodes. Written by Roger West, University of Illinois at Springfield 01/19/2006

addAtPosition

public boolean addAtPosition(java.lang.Object obj,
                             java.lang.Object parent,
                             int position)
Add the specified item to this NaryTree as a new child of the first existing instance of the specified parent item in this NaryTree, as determined using a level-order traversal, at the specified position relative to the other child nodes. If the specified parent item does not exist in this NaryTree, the new item is added as a child in the last position of the root node. If the specified position is invalid, this method fails.

Parameters:
obj: - the new item to be added
parent: - the item to which the new item should be added
position: - the position relative to existing child nodes

remove

public boolean remove()
Remove the first item in the NaryTree. By default, the first item is considered to be the root item. The new root will be the root's first child, if it exists. If the root has no child nodes, the tree will be emptied. Throws NoSuchElementException if tree is empty.
